## Performance Context
OrdMap variant (after promote) uses Indexes (4× OrdMap, ~120MB at 200K). Replace with SortedVecIndexes (~20MB). With post-transact demotion (bd-nwva), OrdMap variant is only live during transact — SortedVecIndexes primarily reduce PROMOTION COST: collect+sort is cheaper than N×OrdMap-insert.

Promotion cost: Indexes (OrdMap): ~45ms at 200K. SortedVecIndexes: ~15ms (collect+single sort_all).

## Resolved Type Decisions
1. StoreRepr::OrdMap changes indexes field from Indexes to SortedVecIndexes
2. promote() builds SortedVecIndexes::from_datoms() + sort_all() instead of Indexes::from_datoms()
3. insert() uses SortedVecIndexes::insert() (O(1) push, marks unsorted). Indexes are NOT re-sorted after each insert — they're only sorted on query or before demotion.
4. indexes() return type changes from Option<&Indexes> to Option<&SortedVecIndexes>. Tests that call eavt_datoms() etc. work because GenericIndexes provides these methods for both backends.
5. With demotion (bd-nwva), the SortedVecIndexes are NEVER queried in normal flow — promote, insert N datoms, demote. No sort_all() needed in the transact path. But for convergence tests that call insert() then indexes(), add sort_all() call inside indexes() accessor.

