## What
`Store::transact` bypasses the promote/demote cycle by merging new datoms directly into the PositionalStore canonical array. The store never leaves Positional form during a single-transaction write. This reduces transact cost from O(N log N) to O(N + K) where N = store size, K = transaction size.

## Why
The current promote/demote per transact is O(2N + 4N log N + K log N) for K new datoms on an N-datom store. The dominant cost is SortedVecIndexes construction during promote (400K Datom clones at 100K datoms) which demote immediately discards. For balanced workloads with frequent writes, this is catastrophic.

Merge-sort splice is O(N + K): one merge scan to produce the new canonical array, one LIVE bitvector rebuild, and an O(K) fingerprint update via XOR homomorphism (INV-FERR-074). Permutation arrays are OnceLock (lazy, invalidated by the splice).

This is MORE aligned with accretive design (principle 4, spec/09) than promote/demote — the store stays in Positional form, which is the prolly tree leaf precursor.

