**PHASE-TARGETED RESEARCH — Phase 4c, NOT Phase 4b**. Filed during session 020 cross-phase optimization analysis. Evaluate at Phase 4c planning gate. If the composition with sharding partition routing (per INV-FERR-017) holds, graduate to execution. **Do NOT file as Phase 4b execution; the bd-snnh data shows EAVT is already at 2.2µs/p50 with massive headroom.**

**What**: A mixture-of-experts (MoE) learned indexing architecture for the EAVT canonical array. Instead of a single global learned index over all 100M+ datoms, build **128 small specialized learned indexes** (PGM-index or similar), each covering a partition of the entity space (partitioned by the first 7 bits of the entity prefix → 128 partitions). Routing is one bit shift + array index — literally one CPU cycle. Each expert is L1-resident, more accurate than a global model (specialized to its slice's distribution), and independently trainable.

**Why**: Serves spec/03 INV-FERR-027 (read latency at scale) and Tier 3 performance objective. The current EAVT path uses interpolation_search on a global canonical array. A learned index (bd-pgm-eavt or similar) improves on this by replacing the search algorithm with a model. **MoE replaces ONE global model with 128 specialized models** — each specialized for a smaller, more uniform sub-distribution, with O(1) routing.

The mathematical advantage: a global model averages over the entire data distribution, paying constant cost on the worst-case region. A specialized model fits a smaller region exactly, paying smaller constant cost. Specialization beats generalization for distributionally-skewed sub-problems (a known result from MoE literature in ML — Shazeer et al. 2017).

**Why this is a Phase 4c bead, not Phase 4b**:

Phase 4c introduces sharding (INV-FERR-017, bd-85j.14, bd-9khc) which partitions the entity space across nodes via `entity_hash mod N`. Sharding and MoE indexing are **the same routing pattern at different granularities**:

| Pattern | Granularity | Layer |
|---------|-------------|-------|
| Sharding | Across nodes | Federation |
| MoE indexing | Within a node | Local query |

A federated query routes by entity hash to find the right shard, then within the shard routes by entity prefix to find the right expert. **Same routing function, two levels of dispatch.** Filing them together means the routing layer is built once and serves both. Filing them separately means duplicating the dispatch logic.

The deeper composition: a federated shard IS an MoE expert that lives on a remote node. A local MoE expert IS a shard that happens to be co-located. The substrate's view of "where does this entity live" is uniformly answered by hash routing, regardless of whether the answer is "expert 7 on this node" or "shard 23 on the remote node."

**Honest framing**: this bead is filed at Phase 4c targeting because the routing infrastructure and the partition story are being built for sharding anyway. As a standalone Phase 4b bead, MoE indexing would be ~4 weeks of work introducing a new dispatch layer. As a Phase 4c rider on the sharding refactor, it's ~2 weeks of additional work on top of the already-touched routing code.

Per the extreme-software-optimization skill discipline: opportunity score **5.3** (Impact 4 × Confidence 4 / Effort 3 — lower effort because it rides the sharding refactor). Above 2.0; honest.

