**What**: Add a Piecewise Geometric Model index (PGM-index, Ferragina & Vinciguerra 2020) as an *alternative* lookup path for the EAVT canonical array, behind a feature flag for A/B comparison against the existing `interpolation_search`. The PGM-index uses recursive linear regression to predict the position of a key with bounded error ε, then a small bounded scan (≤2ε) confirms the exact match.

**Why**: Serves spec/03 INV-FERR-027 (read latency at scale). The current `interpolation_search` exploits BLAKE3 uniformity to give O(log log n) probes (validated by bd-snnh: EAVT p50 = 2.2µs at 100M). PGM-index goes one step further: it learns a bounded-error model from the data once at construction time, then each lookup is `O(log log ε)` probes within a constant-bounded range. For BLAKE3-uniform 8-byte entity prefixes, the model is essentially trivial — a single linear segment captures the entire 100M dataset with ε ≈ √n ≈ 10K. One level of recursion brings ε down to ≤32 (single cache line), giving 2-3 cache misses per lookup vs the current 5-7.

**Honest framing**: This is a **modest, mathematically clean improvement** on an already-fast path. EAVT is currently at 2.2µs/p50 with 5× headroom to the spec budget. PGM-index reduces probe count from ~5-7 to ~2-3, which translates to ~30-50% latency reduction (2.2µs → 1.3-1.7µs). This is real and worth doing, but it is NOT the 13× speedup my pre-correction pitch claimed. The pre-correction was confused: interpolation search is already capturing most of the BLAKE3-uniformity benefit, and PGM-index compounds with that, not replaces it.

