## Dependencies
- **Depends on**: bd-bdvf (B01 — spec), bd-k5bv (C8 rename — NodeId in TxId layout)
- **Blocks**: bd-6j0r (B09 — signing_message), bd-3t63 (B08 — fingerprint + tx_entity)

**What**: Replace the dense `BitVec<u64, Lsb0>` LIVE bitvector inside `PositionalStore` with a Roaring bitmap (`RoaringBitmap`, the `roaring` crate). The LIVE set tracks which canonical positions are LIVE (the latest assertion for their `(entity, attribute, value)` triple per INV-FERR-029). Roaring uses a hybrid representation (sorted u16 arrays for sparse buckets, dense bitmaps for full buckets, run-length encoding for contiguous ranges) that compresses sparse-or-clustered sets by 10-100×.

**Why**: Serves INV-FERR-029 (LIVE bitvector correctness) and the GOALS.md Tier 3 performance objective. The current `BitVec` implementation uses 1 bit per canonical position regardless of LIVE density. At 100M datoms, that is 12.5 MB even when 99.9% of datoms are LIVE (the typical CALM monotone-write workload from doc 003). Roaring compresses this to ~100 KB-1 MB depending on retraction patterns. The compression is real, the crate is mature, and the semantics are preserved by construction (Roaring IS a set representation of u32; LIVE positions are u32; the set is identical).

**Honest framing**: This is the **single highest-leverage execution bead** in the post-bd-snnh perf set. Unlike PGM-index or prefetch optimizations (which improve already-fast paths by 10-30%), Roaring delivers 10-100× memory compression on the LIVE bitvector — the dominant non-canonical memory consumer. The headline win is *memory*, not query latency.

Per the extreme-software-optimization skill discipline, the opportunity score is **5.3** (Impact 4 × Confidence 4 / Effort 3), well above the 2.0 cutoff.

