## Refinement Sketch
- **Abstract** (spec says): INV-FERR-027 Level 1 requires P99.99 read latency < 10ms at 100M datoms. For entity-lookup (the dominant query), this requires O(1) or O(log log n) access. A monotone minimal perfect hash (MMPH) maps N keys to [0, N) with zero collisions and preserves the sort order of the input keys — enabling O(1) entity lookup on frozen stores.
- **Concrete** (code must): `MphBackend` trait defines the interface (build from sorted keys, lookup, num_slots). `ChdBackend` implements compress-hash-displace (CHD) in ~120 lines of safe Rust using two BLAKE3-derived hash functions on EntityId bytes. `Mph` wraps the backend + stored keys for verification (reject non-construction keys). `PositionalStore` gains an `OnceLock<Mph>` field — lazily built on first `entity_lookup()` call.
- **Coupling** (verified by): Postconditions 4-6 — proptest verifying completeness (zero false negatives for construction keys), correctness (returns right position), and rejection (absent keys return None). The trait abstraction (postcondition 3) ensures backend swappability without callers changing.

## Edge Cases
| Scenario | Behavior |
|----------|----------|
| Empty key set | Mph { backend: ChdBackend { num_slots: 0 }, keys: [] }. contains returns false. |
| Single key | 1 bucket, 1 slot, displacement 0. contains in O(1). |
| MAX_DISPLACEMENT exhausted | build returns None. OnceLock stores None. Fallback to binary search. |
| Absent key | backend.lookup returns arbitrary slot. keys[slot_to_key_idx[slot]] != key → contains false. |
| Present key | backend.lookup → slot → slot_to_key_idx → key_idx → keys[key_idx] == key → true. |

